{"title_page": "Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = File:134_Houston_Street.jpeg\n| caption             = The building's entrance in 2019\n| map_type            = Georgia (U.S. state)\n| map_caption         = Location within Georgia\n| map_dot_label       = 314 Houston Street, Savannah\n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = 134\u2013142 Houston Street<ref>[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/305898E3-EEF2-4640-ADC8-333993874854 Photo Record] - Georgia Historical Society</ref>\n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = Hidden Well Acupuncture<ref>[https://hiddenwellacupuncture.com/ Hidden Well Acupuncture website]</ref>\n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32.07589|-81.086098|format=dms}}\n| start_date          =\n| completion_date     = {{Start date and age|1801}}\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 1\n| floor_area          = 3,722 [[square feet|sq. ft]]<ref>[https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/134-Houston-St-Savannah-GA-31401/131743982_zpid/ 134 Houston St, Savannah, GA 31401] - Zillow.com</ref>\n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\nThe '''Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten''' is located at 134 Houston Street in the [[Savannah Historic District (Savannah, Georgia)|historic district]] of [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Built of brick, the building stands at the corner of Houston and East York Streets in the southeastern corner of Greene Square.\n\nThe building was constructed in 1801. It became the Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten in 1899, founded by George Johnson Baldwin (1856\u20131927) and his sisters as a memorial to their mother, Kate A. Baldwin (1830\u20131898).<ref name=shc>[https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/02834/ \"Collection Number: 02834. Collection Title: Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten Records, 1899-1938\"] - The Southern Historical Collection, The Wilson Library, [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]</ref> It was incorporated in 1899 as a \"benevolent and charitable institution for the free training, instruction, and education of young children under the [[kindergarten]] system of education, so as to inculcate in them habits of industry and morality and fit them for entrance into institutions of higher education.\"<ref name=ghs>[http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%201688-ead.xml;query=;brand=default \"Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten (Savannah, Ga.) photograph album\"] - [[Georgia Historical Society]]</ref>\n\nThe project was continued by George Baldwin's children, George Hull Baldwin and Dorothea Irwin, under the direction of Martha G. Waring (1873\u20131943).<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/124246728/martha-gallaudet-waring Martha Gallaudet Waring] at FindAGrave.com</ref> Under the supervision of Massachusetts native Hortense M. Orcutt<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/22/archives/miss-hortense-m-orcutt-savannah-kindergarten-head-had-taught-in-new.html \"MISS HORTENSE M. ORCUTT; Savannah Kindergarten Head Had Taught in New York.\"] - ''[[New York Times]]'', January 22, 1936</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37203530/obituary-for-hortense-orcutt/ \"Obituary for Hortense Orcutt\"] - ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'', January 23, 1936, via Newspapers.com</ref> from 1907 for the subsequent 25 years, it grew into a popular system of [[kindergarten]]s and a training school (known as the Normal Department) for kindergarten teachers,<ref name=shc/> with as many as five kindergartens in operation at one time.<ref name=ghs/> The network educated approximately four thousand children between 1899 and 1943.\n\nAfter the death of Hortense Orcutt in 1936, the training school was discontinued, but the Baldwins continued the East Side Kindergarten, and nine other kindergartens continued under the auspices of the public schools, a church and other organizations.<ref>[https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/02834/#folder_1a#1 \"Kate Baldwin Kindergarten Papers, 1899\u20131938\"], University of North Carolina Chapel Hill</ref>  \n\n[[File:314_Houston_Street_2.jpeg|thumb|left|The East York Street side of the building]]\n\nThe school subsequently became known as the Savannah Nursery School and the [[Montessori]] Pre-School.<ref name=ghs/>\n\nKate Baldwin, the wife of Daniel H. Baldwin, Sr. (1825\u20131887),<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/76111574/daniel-h_-baldwin Daniel H. Baldwin (1825\u20131887)] at FindAGrave.com</ref> died on November 11, 1898, aged 68. She is buried in Savannah's [[Bonaventure Cemetery]].<ref name=grave>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/76111640/kate-a_-baldwin Kate A. Baldwin (1830\u20131898)] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:134_Houston_Street.png|A close-up of the plaque above the main door\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em}}\n\n==External links==\n;Photographs from 1932 of the kindergarten\n*[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/305898E3-EEF2-4640-ADC8-333993874854 Exterior]\n*[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/5059A533-C3EB-48B9-9FD2-263627062858 Interior] \n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1801]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1899]]\n[[Category:1899 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Kindergarten]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten\n| native_name= \n| former_names        = \n| image               = File:134_Houston_Street.jpeg\n| caption             = The building's entrance in 2019\n| map_type            = Georgia (U.S. state)\n| map_caption         = Location within Georgia\n| map_dot_label       = 314 Houston Street, Savannah\n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = 134\u2013142 Houston Street<ref>[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/305898E3-EEF2-4640-ADC8-333993874854 Photo Record] - Georgia Historical Society</ref>\n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = Hidden Well Acupuncture<ref>[https://hiddenwellacupuncture.com/ Hidden Well Acupuncture website]</ref>\n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32.07589|-81.086098|format=dms}}\n| start_date          =\n| completion_date     = {{Start date and age|1801}}\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 1\n| floor_area          = 3,722 [[square feet|sq. ft]]<ref>[https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/134-Houston-St-Savannah-GA-31401/131743982_zpid/ 134 Houston St, Savannah, GA 31401] - Zillow.com</ref>\n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\nThe '''Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten''' is located at 134 Houston Street in the [[Savannah Historic District (Savannah, Georgia)|historic district]] of [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Built of brick, the building stands at the corner of Houston and East York Streets in the southeastern corner of Greene Square.\n\nThe building was constructed in 1801. It became the Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten in 1899, and was founded by George Johnson Baldwin (1856\u20131927) and his sisters as a memorial to their mother, Kate A. Baldwin (1830\u20131898).<ref name=shc>[https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/02834/ \"Collection Number: 02834. Collection Title: Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten Records, 1899-1938\"] - The Southern Historical Collection, The Wilson Library, [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]</ref> It was incorporated in 1899 as a \"benevolent and charitable institution for the free training, instruction, and education of young children under the [[kindergarten]] system of education, so as to inculcate in them habits of industry and morality and fit them for entrance into institutions of higher education.\"<ref name=ghs>[http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%201688-ead.xml;query=;brand=default \"Kate Baldwin Free Kindergarten (Savannah, Ga.) photograph album\"] - [[Georgia Historical Society]]</ref>\n\nThe project was continued by George Baldwin's children, George Hull Baldwin and Dorothea Irwin, under the direction of Martha G. Waring (1873\u20131943).<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/124246728/martha-gallaudet-waring Martha Gallaudet Waring] at FindAGrave.com</ref> Under the supervision of Massachusetts native Hortense M. Orcutt<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/22/archives/miss-hortense-m-orcutt-savannah-kindergarten-head-had-taught-in-new.html \"MISS HORTENSE M. ORCUTT; Savannah Kindergarten Head Had Taught in New York.\"] - ''[[New York Times]]'', January 22, 1936</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37203530/obituary-for-hortense-orcutt/ \"Obituary for Hortense Orcutt\"] - ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'', January 23, 1936, via Newspapers.com</ref> from 1907 for the subsequent 25 years, it grew into a popular system of [[kindergarten]]s and a training school (known as the Normal Department) for kindergarten teachers,<ref name=shc/> with as many as five kindergartens in operation at one time.<ref name=ghs/> The network educated approximately four thousand children between 1899 and 1943.\n\nAfter the death of Hortense Orcutt in 1936, the training school was discontinued, but the Baldwins continued the East Side Kindergarten, and nine other kindergartens continued under the auspices of the public schools, a church and other organizations.<ref>[https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/02834/#folder_1a#1 \"Kate Baldwin Kindergarten Papers, 1899\u20131938\"], University of North Carolina Chapel Hill</ref>  \n\n[[File:314_Houston_Street_2.jpeg|thumb|left|The East York Street side of the building]]\n\nThe school subsequently became known as the Savannah Nursery School and the [[Montessori]] Pre-School.<ref name=ghs/>\n\nKate Baldwin, the wife of Daniel H. Baldwin, Sr. (1825\u20131887),<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/76111574/daniel-h_-baldwin Daniel H. Baldwin (1825\u20131887)] at FindAGrave.com</ref> died on November 11, 1898, aged 68. She is buried in Savannah's [[Bonaventure Cemetery]].<ref name=grave>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/76111640/kate-a_-baldwin Kate A. Baldwin (1830\u20131898)] at FindAGrave.com</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:134_Houston_Street.png|A close-up of the plaque above the main door\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em}}\n\n==External links==\n;Photographs from 1932 of the kindergarten\n*[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/305898E3-EEF2-4640-ADC8-333993874854 Exterior]\n*[https://georgiahistory.pastperfectonline.com/photo/5059A533-C3EB-48B9-9FD2-263627062858 Interior] \n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1801]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1899]]\n[[Category:1899 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\