{"title_page": "Charles D. Copp", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Charles D. Copp\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1840|04|12}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1912|11|02|1840|04|12}}\n|birth_place   = Warren County, New Hampshire\n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = Middle Cemetery\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|New Hampshire}} [[9th Regiment New Hampshire Volunteer Infantry]]\n|battles       = [[Battle of Fredericksburg]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles Dearborne Copp''' (April 12, 1840 to November 2, 1912) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Copp received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] in Virginia on 13 December 1862. He was honored with the award on 28 June 1890.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Projects\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=385 |title=Charles Dearborne Copp |accessdate=28 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031151801/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=385 |archive-date=31 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nCopp was born in Warren County, New Hampshire on 12 April 1840. He enlisted into the 9th New Hampshire Infantry. He died on 2 November 1912 and his remains are interred at the Middle Cemetery in Massachusetts.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Seized the regimental colors, the color bearer having been shot down, and, waving them, rallied the regiment under a heavy fire.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Projects\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Copp, Charles D.}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of New Hampshire in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Charles D. Copp\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1840|04|12}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1912|11|02|1840|04|12}}\n|birth_place   = Warren County, New Hampshire\n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = Middle Cemetery\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|New Hampshire}} [[9th New Hampshire Volunteer Infantry]]\n|battles       = [[Battle of Fredericksburg]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles Dearborne Copp''' (April 12, 1840 to November 2, 1912) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Copp received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] in Virginia on 13 December 1862. He was honored with the award on 28 June 1890.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Projects\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=385 |title=Charles Dearborne Copp |accessdate=28 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031151801/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=385 |archive-date=31 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nCopp was born in Warren County, New Hampshire on 12 April 1840. He enlisted into the 9th New Hampshire Infantry. He died on 2 November 1912 and his remains are interred at the Middle Cemetery in Massachusetts.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Seized the regimental colors, the color bearer having been shot down, and, waving them, rallied the regiment under a heavy fire.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Projects\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Copp, Charles D.}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of New Hampshire in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_D._Copp"}
{"title_page": "Ding ware", "text_new": "{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the bronze and ceramic [[Ding (vessel)|ding]] cauldrons of ancient China.}}\n[[File:Bowl (Wan) with Peony, Chrysanthemum, and Prunus Sprays LACMA M.73.48.101.jpg|thumb|Bowl (Wan) with Peony, Chrysanthemum, and Prunus Sprays, described by  [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art|LACMA]] as \"wheel-thrown stoneware with impressed decoration, transparent glaze, and banded metal rim\", though others would call it porcelain. 12th century]]\n[[File:Dish (Pan) with Garden Landscape LACMA M.73.48.106.jpg|thumb|Dish (Pan) with Garden Landscape, described by [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art|LACMA]] as \"molded stoneware with impressed decoration, transparent glaze, and banded metal rim\", 13th century, diameter 5.5 in. (14 cm)]]\n\n'''Ding ware''', '''Ting ware''' ({{zh|c=\u5b9a\u74f7|p=D\u00ecngc\u00ed}}) or '''Dingyao''' were [[Chinese ceramics]], mostly [[porcelain]], produced in the prefecture of [[Dingzhou]] ([[Wade-Giles|formerly]] [[romanization of Chinese|romanized]] as \"Ting-chou\") in [[Hebei]] in northern China. The main kilns were at [[Jiancicun]] or Jianci in [[Quyang County]].  They were produced between the [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] and [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]] [[list of Chinese dynasties|dynasties]] of [[imperial China]], though their finest period was in the 11th century, under the [[Northern Song]].<ref>Vainker, 93\u201395; Osborne, 184\u2013185</ref>  The [[kiln]]s \"were in almost constant operation from the early eighth until the mid-fourteenth century.\"<ref>[[British Museum]], [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=3179914&partId=1&ware=11262&page=1  \"dish\"], [[Percival David Foundation|PDF]].163, quote in expanded \"Curator's comments\"</ref>\n\nThe most characteristic wares are thin porcelains with a white or greyish body and a nearly transparent white-tinted [[ceramic glaze|glaze]],<ref>described as \"porcelain\" by Rawson, 82; Vainker, 95</ref> though they are classed as [[stoneware]] by some.<ref>for example [https://www.britannica.com/art/Ding-ware Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica] and the [[LACMA]]; other sources cannot make up their mind \u2013 [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=3179914&partId=1&ware=11262&page=1 here the British Museum describes a dish as both porcelain and stoneware on the same page]\n(\"stoneware\" in expanded \"Curator's comments\"). Osborne, 184\u2013185 avoids using either term.</ref>  Chemical analysis has shown that they were often made entirely of a [[kaolin]]itic clay without any [[petuntse]] or \"porcelain stone\".<ref>Valenstein, 92</ref>  They are mostly decorated with uncoloured designs that are incised or in very shallow [[relief]].\n\nDing ware was the most famous northern Chinese white ware under the Song, although there was increasing competition from the [[Qingbai ware]] from [[Jingdezhen ware|Jingdezhen]] in the south, which by the end of the Song had eclipsed Ding ware, achieving a predominance it has maintained in subsequent centuries.  A key event in this process was the flight of the remaining [[Northern Song]] court to the south, after they lost control of the north in the disastrous [[Jin\u2013Song Wars#War against the Northern Song|Jin-Song wars of the 1120s]]. A new [[Southern Song]] court was based in [[Hangzhou]].<ref>Rawson, 84; Vainker, 105</ref>   This may have been accompanied by the movement of potters to Jingdezhen.<ref>Rawson, 82</ref>\n\n==Wares==\n[[File:Bottle, Ding ware, Hebei province, China, Northern Song dynasty, 11th-early 12th century AD, porcelain with iron pigment under transparent ivory-toned glaze - Freer Gallery of Art - DSC05557.JPG|thumb|[[Song dynasty]] Ding [[porcelain]] bottle with iron pigment under a transparent ivory-toned glaze, c. 1100.  Both the closed shape and the painted [[underglaze decoration]] are uncommon in Ding.]]\nThe white glaze was noted for a slight cream or ivory tint, apart from which it was transparent. Earlier, pre-Song, pieces had a blueish tint as (like [[Xing ware]]) they were fired with wood, producing a [[reducing atmosphere]]. A change to firing with [[coal]], probably in the 10th century, produced the tint described as \"ivory\".<ref>Vainker, 95, 124</ref>\n\nOther \"secondary\" wares had monochrome glazes in different colours:<ref>Vainker, 99 quoted</ref> a very rare black, various shades of red and brown, gold and green.<ref>Vainker, 99; Valenstein, 92; Osborne, 185</ref>  These \"are better known through literature than through surviving examples ... only the red and black are represented by entire pieces\".<ref>Vainker, 99 quoted</ref>  These may lack any other decoration. Song court taste valued plain wares decorated only by exquisite monochrome glazes in colours that were very difficult to achieve, such as the famous [[Ru ware]], produced for only 40 years, and with surviving pieces totalling a two-figure number.<ref>Vainker, 99\u2013101</ref> Another rare group is white with painted [[underglaze decoration]] in a brown derived from iron oxides.<ref>Osborne, 185</ref>\n\nPieces produced in Ding ware were mostly open vessels of a relatively small size, with shapes and decoration often borrowed from metalwork, as in the bowls with lobed rims.  Vases are relatively uncommon.<ref>Osborne, 185</ref>  Initially pieces were mostly thrown on the [[potter's wheel]], often with templates, but in the late 11th century [[Molding (process)|mould]]s began to be used, which included the inside decoration, previously carved or incised with a knife on the [[leather-hard]] piece. Any decoration on the outside of pieces continued to be hand-carved for some time.<ref>Vainker, 96</ref>\n\nWhile the decoration was hand-carved, it was mostly scrolling plant-forms including lotus and [[peony]], with some simple animals such as ducks and fish.  These were \"generally rather open and well spaced, executed with remarkable fluency and an apparently unfailing sense of compositional balance\". Moulds allowed more complexity, including scenes with children, landscapes and other animals.<ref>Osborne, 185 (quoted)</ref>\n\nThe firing process was with bowls placed upside down in the kiln, which meant that the glaze had to be wiped from the rim, which left a rough rim, and many pieces were given a thin metal rim in silver or a \"brassy alloy\".<ref>Valenstein, 89; Osborne, 185; Vainker, 95</ref>  The Ding kilns developed stepped [[saggar]]s, allowing several bowls, slightly reducing in size, to be fired in the same saggar, increasing the efficiency of kiln loading.<ref>Vainker, 95</ref>\n\nTraditional [[East Asia]]n thinking only classifies pottery into [[earthenware]] and porcelain, without the intermediate European class of stoneware, and the many local types of stoneware such as Ding ware were mostly classed as porcelain, though often not white and translucent.  Terms such as \"porcellaneous\" or \"near-porcelain\" may be used in such cases.<ref>Valenstein, 22, 59\u201360, 72</ref>\n\n==Fame and influence==\nThe range and output of the wares was large, producing ceramics of high quality for the wealthy merchant class and the [[scholar-literati]] class, as well as tributary ceramics of the highest quality for the imperial court.  A chronicle records that \"the king went to pay his respects at the Zongde Dian and offered up 2,000 pieces of Ding ware decorated with gold\",<ref>Rawson, 82</ref> but other records suggest that the rough rims and \"teardrops\" formed by running glaze meant that they were not considered fine enough for use by the emperor himself, or at least had become so regarded by the late Southern Song.<ref>Vainker, 95\u201396</ref>\n\nDing ware was later grouped as one of the [[Five Famous Kilns]]. It heavily influenced the early white wares of [[Jingdezhen]], where the white porcelain preceding [[Qingbai ware]] is known as \"Southern Ding\", and Qingbai also shows considerable influence in its decoration.<ref>Vainker, 97\u201398, 124</ref>\n\nDing production continued under the [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)]], non-Chinese interlopers from [[Manchuria]].  Jin court taste was very different from the Song, favouring elegant [[plant-scroll]] designs, now mostly moulded, which were more intricate than those already produced under the Northern Song.  There was renewed borrowing from T'ang decoration in silver, lacquer and stone, and from metalware shapes, such as lobed or notched rims to bowls and plates.  The increased complexity in scrolling plant designs was significant for the history of Chinese pottery; these monochrome designs in very shallow relief formed the basis of the iconic vocabulary of later [[blue and white pottery]], pioneered at Jingdezhen, and of immense influence globally.<ref>Rawson, 81\u201388</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nTea bowl. Southern Song. Ding ware. British Museum.jpg|Rare black-glazed bowl, Northern Song, with copper rim.\nBowl with notched rim, Ding ware, Hebei province, China, Northern Song dynasty, 11th-early 12th century AD, porcelain with iron glaze - Freer Gallery of Art - DSC05562.JPG|Rare brown-glazed bowl, Northern Song, with notched rim.\nDish (Pan) with a Pair of Mandarin Ducks LACMA 54.37.4.jpg|Dish with a Pair of Mandarin Ducks, moulded with impressed decoration and metal rim, diameter 5.5 in. (13.97 cm)\nIncense Burner (Lu) in the Form of an Ancient Bronze Container (Lian) LACMA AC1998.90.1.jpg|Incense Burner (Lu) in the form of an ancient [[Ritual bronze]] container (Lian), height 4.5 in. (11.43 cm)\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Osborne, Harold (ed), ''The Oxford Companion to the Decorative Arts'', 1975, OUP, {{ISBN|0198661134}}\n* [[Jessica Rawson|Rawson, Jessica]], ''Chinese Ornament: The Lotus and the Dragon'', 1984, British Museum Publications, {{ISBN|0714114316}}\n* Vainker, S.J., ''Chinese Pottery and Porcelain'', 1991, British Museum Press, 9780714114705\n* Valenstein, S. (1998). ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/38422/rec/3 A handbook of Chinese ceramics]'' (fully available online), Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York. {{ISBN|9780870995149}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Chinese ceramics}}\n{{Porcelain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ding ware}}\n[[Category:Chinese porcelain]]\n[[Category:Chinese pottery]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the bronze and ceramic [[Ding (vessel)|ding]] cauldrons of ancient China.}}\n[[File:Bowl (Wan) with Peony, Chrysanthemum, and Prunus Sprays LACMA M.73.48.101.jpg|thumb|Bowl (Wan) with Peony, Chrysanthemum, and Prunus Sprays, described by  [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art|LACMA]] as \"wheel-thrown stoneware with impressed decoration, transparent glaze, and banded metal rim\", though others would call it porcelain. 12th century]]\n[[File:Dish (Pan) with Garden Landscape LACMA M.73.48.106.jpg|thumb|Dish (Pan) with Garden Landscape, described by [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art|LACMA]] as \"molded stoneware with impressed decoration, transparent glaze, and banded metal rim\", 13th century, diameter 5.5 in. (14 cm)]]\n\n'''Ding ware''', '''Ting ware''' ({{zh|c=\u5b9a\u74f7|p=D\u00ecngc\u00ed}}) or '''Dingyao''' were [[Chinese ceramics]], mostly [[porcelain]], produced in the prefecture of [[Dingzhou]] ([[Wade-Giles|formerly]] [[romanization of Chinese|romanized]] as \"Ting-chou\") in [[Hebei]] in northern China. The main kilns were at [[Jiancicun]] or Jianci in [[Quyang County]].  They were produced between the [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] and [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]] [[list of Chinese dynasties|dynasties]] of [[imperial China]], though their finest period was in the 11th century, under the [[Northern Song]].<ref>Vainker, 93\u201395; Osborne, 184\u2013185</ref>  The [[kiln]]s \"were in almost constant operation from the early eighth until the mid-fourteenth century.\"<ref>[[British Museum]], [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=3179914&partId=1&ware=11262&page=1  \"dish\"], [[Percival David Foundation|PDF]].163, quote in expanded \"Curator's comments\"</ref>\n\nThe most characteristic wares are thin porcelains with a white or greyish body and a nearly transparent white-tinted [[ceramic glaze|glaze]],<ref>described as \"porcelain\" by Rawson, 82; Vainker, 95</ref> though they are classed as [[stoneware]] by some.<ref>for example [https://www.britannica.com/art/Ding-ware Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica] and the [[LACMA]]; other sources cannot make up their mind \u2013 [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=3179914&partId=1&ware=11262&page=1 here the British Museum describes a dish as both porcelain and stoneware on the same page]\n(\"stoneware\" in expanded \"Curator's comments\"). Osborne, 184\u2013185 avoids using either term.</ref>  Chemical analysis has shown that they were often made entirely of a [[kaolin]]itic clay without any [[petuntse]] or \"porcelain stone\".<ref>Valenstein, 92</ref>  They are mostly decorated with uncoloured designs that are incised or in very shallow [[relief]].\n\nDing ware was the most famous northern Chinese white ware under the Song, although there was increasing competition from the [[Qingbai ware]] from [[Jingdezhen ware|Jingdezhen]] in the south, which by the end of the Song had eclipsed Ding ware, achieving a predominance it has maintained in subsequent centuries.  A key event in this process was the flight of the remaining [[Northern Song]] court to the south, after they lost control of the north in the disastrous [[Jin\u2013Song Wars#War against the Northern Song|Jin-Song wars of the 1120s]]. A new [[Southern Song]] court was based in [[Hangzhou]].<ref>Rawson, 84; Vainker, 105</ref>   This may have been accompanied by the movement of potters to Jingdezhen.<ref>Rawson, 82</ref>\n\n==Wares==\n[[File:Bottle, Ding ware, Hebei province, China, Northern Song dynasty, 11th-early 12th century AD, porcelain with iron pigment under transparent ivory-toned glaze - Freer Gallery of Art - DSC05557.JPG|thumb|[[Song dynasty]] Ding [[porcelain]] bottle with iron pigment under a transparent ivory-toned glaze, c. 1100.  Both the closed shape and the painted [[underglaze decoration]] are uncommon in Ding.]]\nThe white glaze was noted for a slight cream or ivory tint, apart from which it was transparent. Earlier, pre-Song, pieces had a blueish tint as (like [[Xing ware]]) they were fired with wood, producing a [[reducing atmosphere]]. A change to firing with [[coal]], probably in the 10th century, produced the tint described as \"ivory\".<ref>Vainker, 95, 124</ref>\n\nOther \"secondary\" wares had monochrome glazes in different colours:<ref>Vainker, 99 quoted</ref> a very rare black, various shades of red and brown, gold and green.<ref>Vainker, 99; Valenstein, 92; Osborne, 185</ref>  These \"are better known through literature than through surviving examples ... only the red and black are represented by entire pieces\".<ref>Vainker, 99 quoted</ref>  These may lack any other decoration. Song court taste valued plain wares decorated only by exquisite monochrome glazes in colours that were very difficult to achieve, such as the famous [[Ru ware]], produced for only 40 years, and with surviving pieces totalling a two-figure number.<ref>Vainker, 99\u2013101</ref> Another rare group is white with painted [[underglaze decoration]] in a brown derived from iron oxides.<ref>Osborne, 185</ref>\n\nPieces produced in Ding ware were mostly open vessels of a relatively small size, with shapes and decoration often borrowed from metalwork, as in the bowls with lobed rims.  Vases are relatively uncommon.<ref>Osborne, 185</ref>  Initially pieces were mostly thrown on the [[potter's wheel]], often with templates, but in the late 11th century [[mould]]s began to be used, which included the inside decoration, previously carved or incised with a knife on the [[leather-hard]] piece. Any decoration on the outside of pieces continued to be hand-carved for some time.<ref>Vainker, 96</ref>\n\nWhile the decoration was hand-carved, it was mostly scrolling plant-forms including lotus and [[peony]], with some simple animals such as ducks and fish.  These were \"generally rather open and well spaced, executed with remarkable fluency and an apparently unfailing sense of compositional balance\". Moulds allowed more complexity, including scenes with children, landscapes and other animals.<ref>Osborne, 185 (quoted)</ref>\n\nThe firing process was with bowls placed upside down in the kiln, which meant that the glaze had to be wiped from the rim, which left a rough rim, and many pieces were given a thin metal rim in silver or a \"brassy alloy\".<ref>Valenstein, 89; Osborne, 185; Vainker, 95</ref>  The Ding kilns developed stepped [[saggar]]s, allowing several bowls, slightly reducing in size, to be fired in the same saggar, increasing the efficiency of kiln loading.<ref>Vainker, 95</ref>\n\nTraditional [[East Asia]]n thinking only classifies pottery into [[earthenware]] and porcelain, without the intermediate European class of stoneware, and the many local types of stoneware such as Ding ware were mostly classed as porcelain, though often not white and translucent.  Terms such as \"porcellaneous\" or \"near-porcelain\" may be used in such cases.<ref>Valenstein, 22, 59\u201360, 72</ref>\n\n==Fame and influence==\nThe range and output of the wares was large, producing ceramics of high quality for the wealthy merchant class and the [[scholar-literati]] class, as well as tributary ceramics of the highest quality for the imperial court.  A chronicle records that \"the king went to pay his respects at the Zongde Dian and offered up 2,000 pieces of Ding ware decorated with gold\",<ref>Rawson, 82</ref> but other records suggest that the rough rims and \"teardrops\" formed by running glaze meant that they were not considered fine enough for use by the emperor himself, or at least had become so regarded by the late Southern Song.<ref>Vainker, 95\u201396</ref>\n\nDing ware was later grouped as one of the [[Five Famous Kilns]]. It heavily influenced the early white wares of [[Jingdezhen]], where the white porcelain preceding [[Qingbai ware]] is known as \"Southern Ding\", and Qingbai also shows considerable influence in its decoration.<ref>Vainker, 97\u201398, 124</ref>\n\nDing production continued under the [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)]], non-Chinese interlopers from [[Manchuria]].  Jin court taste was very different from the Song, favouring elegant [[plant-scroll]] designs, now mostly moulded, which were more intricate than those already produced under the Northern Song.  There was renewed borrowing from T'ang decoration in silver, lacquer and stone, and from metalware shapes, such as lobed or notched rims to bowls and plates.  The increased complexity in scrolling plant designs was significant for the history of Chinese pottery; these monochrome designs in very shallow relief formed the basis of the iconic vocabulary of later [[blue and white pottery]], pioneered at Jingdezhen, and of immense influence globally.<ref>Rawson, 81\u201388</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nTea bowl. Southern Song. Ding ware. British Museum.jpg|Rare black-glazed bowl, Northern Song, with copper rim.\nBowl with notched rim, Ding ware, Hebei province, China, Northern Song dynasty, 11th-early 12th century AD, porcelain with iron glaze - Freer Gallery of Art - DSC05562.JPG|Rare brown-glazed bowl, Northern Song, with notched rim.\nDish (Pan) with a Pair of Mandarin Ducks LACMA 54.37.4.jpg|Dish with a Pair of Mandarin Ducks, moulded with impressed decoration and metal rim, diameter 5.5 in. (13.97 cm)\nIncense Burner (Lu) in the Form of an Ancient Bronze Container (Lian) LACMA AC1998.90.1.jpg|Incense Burner (Lu) in the form of an ancient [[Ritual bronze]] container (Lian), height 4.5 in. (11.43 cm)\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Osborne, Harold (ed), ''The Oxford Companion to the Decorative Arts'', 1975, OUP, {{ISBN|0198661134}}\n* [[Jessica Rawson|Rawson, Jessica]], ''Chinese Ornament: The Lotus and the Dragon'', 1984, British Museum Publications, {{ISBN|0714114316}}\n* Vainker, S.J., ''Chinese Pottery and Porcelain'', 1991, British Museum Press, 9780714114705\n* Valenstein, S. (1998). ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/38422/rec/3 A handbook of Chinese ceramics]'' (fully available online), Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York. {{ISBN|9780870995149}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Chinese ceramics}}\n{{Porcelain}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ding ware}}\n[[Category:Chinese porcelain]]\n[[Category:Chinese pottery]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMolding (process)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ding_ware"}
{"title_page": "Telegram Corporation", "text_new": "{{About|a Canadian media company||Telegram (disambiguation)}}\n'''Telegram Corporation''' was a Canadian media company created under a joint venture between [[John Bassett]]'s ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' newspaper and businessman [[John David Eaton]] (a member of the prominent [[Eaton family]]), as one of three co-owners of [[CFTO-DT|CFTO-TV]] in 1960.<ref name=\"Nolan2001\">{{cite book|author=Michael Nolan|title=CTV, the Network that Means Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c3FkFx0-uoC&pg=PA20|year=2001|publisher=University of Alberta|isbn=978-0-88864-384-1|page=20}}</ref> When the ''Toronto Telegram'' was shut down in 1971,<ref name=\"Avery2011\">{{cite book|author=Martin Avery|title=Curse of the Maple Leafs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Qg1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|year=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-257-77216-2|page=18}}</ref> the company was renamed [[Baton Broadcasting]] after the <u>Ba</u>ssett and Ea<u>ton</u> families. \n\nBaton Broadcasting was renamed once again to [[Baton Broadcast System]] (BBS) in 1994. The Eatons sold their media stake in 1998, and the Bassetts retained sole control of BBS. That same year, BBS was renamed [[CTV Television Network|CTV]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bell Media}}\n\n[[Category:CTV Television Network]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Defunct broadcasting companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n\n\n{{Canada-corp-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|a Canadian media company||Telegram (disambiguation)}}\n'''Telegram Corporation''' was a Canadian media company created under a joint venture between [[John Bassett]]'s ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' newspaper and the [[Eaton family]], as one of three co-owners of [[CFTO-DT|CFTO-TV]] in 1960.<ref name=\"Nolan2001\">{{cite book|author=Michael Nolan|title=CTV, the Network that Means Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c3FkFx0-uoC&pg=PA20|year=2001|publisher=University of Alberta|isbn=978-0-88864-384-1|page=20}}</ref> When the ''Toronto Telegram'' was shut down in 1971,<ref name=\"Avery2011\">{{cite book|author=Martin Avery|title=Curse of the Maple Leafs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Qg1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|year=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-257-77216-2|page=18}}</ref> the company was renamed [[Baton Broadcasting]] after the <u>Ba</u>ssett and Ea<u>ton</u> families. \n\nBaton Broadcasting was renamed once again to [[Baton Broadcast System]] (BBS) in 1994. The Eatons sold their media stake in 1998, and the Bassetts retained sole control of BBS. That same year, BBS was renamed [[CTV Television Network|CTV]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bell Media}}\n\n[[Category:CTV Television Network]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Defunct broadcasting companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n\n\n{{Canada-corp-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "revised my prior edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telegram_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "Abraham Darby I", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n'''Abraham Darby''', in his later life called '''Abraham Darby the Elder''', now sometimes known for convenience as '''Abraham Darby I''' (14 April 1678 &ndash; 5 May 1717), was the first and best known of [[Abraham Darby (disambiguation)|several men of that name]]. Born into an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[Quaker]] family that played an important role in the [[Industrial Revolution]], Darby developed a method of producing [[pig iron]] in a [[blast furnace]] fuelled by [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] rather than [[charcoal]]. This was a major step forward in the production of iron as a raw material for the Industrial Revolution.\n\n==Early life==\nAbraham Darby was the son of John Darby, a yeoman farmer and locksmith by trade, and his wife Ann Baylies.\nHe was born at [[Woodsettle]], [[Woodsetton]], [[Staffordshire]], just across the county boundary from [[Dudley]], [[Worcestershire]]. He was descended from nobility; his great-grandmother Jane was an [[illegitimate]] child of [[Edward Sutton, 5th Baron Dudley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackcountrysociety.co.uk/articles/duddudley.htm |title=Dud Dudley and Abraham Darby: Forging New Links |author=Carl Higgs |publisher=Black Country Society |access-date=24 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219084159/http://www.blackcountrysociety.co.uk/articles/duddudley.htm |archive-date=19 February 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAbraham's great-grandmother was a sister of the whole blood to [[Dud Dudley]], who claimed to have [[Smelting|smelt]]ed iron using coke as a fuel. Unfortunately, the iron that Dudley produced was not acceptable to the charcoal ironmasters.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W. | title = Dud Dudley's contribution to metallurgy | journal = Historical Metallurgy  | volume = 36  | issue =   1| pages = 43\u201353  | year = 2002}}</ref>  However, this may have inspired his great-grandnephew Darby to perfect this novel method of smelting.\n\nIn [[Birmingham]] in the early 1690s Darby was apprenticed to Jonathan Freeth, a  fellow Quaker and a manufacturer of [[brass]] [[Mill (grinding)|mill]]s for grinding [[malt]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Trinder|first=Barrie Stuart|title=The Darbys of Coalbrookdale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJEaAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2011-12-05|year=1974|publisher=Phillimore|isbn=0-85033-191-9|page=13}}</ref> Here Darby would have seen the use of [[coke (fuel)|coke]] to fuel malting ovens, preventing the [[sulphur]] content of [[coal]] contaminating the resulting [[beer]], but also avoiding the use of the scarcer [[charcoal]] as a fuel.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |title=The Darbys of Coalbrookdale\n  |last=Trinder  |first=Barrie\n  |publisher=Phillimore & Co. / [[Ironbridge Gorge Museum Trust]]\n  |year=1991\n  |origyear=1974\n  |isbn=0-85033-791-7\n  |ref=harv\n  |pages=9\n}}</ref> The combination of these two insights was to lead to Darby's development of the coke-fuelled [[blast furnace]] in 1709.<ref>{{cite book|last=Weissenbacher|first=Manfred|title=Sources of Power: How Energy Forges Human History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dcYHzuFLZP0C&pg=PA194|accessdate=2011-11-27|year=2009|publisher=Praeger|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-0-313-35626-1|page=194}}</ref>\n\nFreeth encouraged Darby to become a highly active member in the Society of Friends, and he remained so all his life. In 1699, when he completed his apprenticeship, he married Mary Sergeant (1678\u20131718) and moved to [[Bristol]], where he set himself up as a malt mill maker.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = Cox  | first = Nancy  | title = Imagination and innovation of an industrial pioneer: The first Abraham Darby  | journal = Industrial Archaeology Review   | volume = 12  | issue = 2  | pages = 127\u2013144 at 128  | year = 1990 | doi=10.1179/iar.1990.12.2.127}}</ref>\n\n==Bristol==\nThere was a small community of [[Quakers]] in Bristol, and Darby soon gained a reputation for skill and enterprise. In 1702 Darby joined a number of fellow Quakers to form the [[Bristol Brass Company]], with works at [[Baptist Mills, Bristol|Baptist Mills]] in Bristol.  He brought in 'Dutchmen' to operate a [[brass]] battery work, making cooking pots and other [[holloware]] under a [[trip hammer]].<ref>Cox, p. 128.</ref>\n\nHe also developed a method for casting pots in '[[green sand (casting)|greensand]]' [[Molding (process)|mould]]s, previously only used for smaller castings.  This enabled pots to be mass-produced and to be thinner than those made by the traditional process of casting in loam moulds.  For this purpose, he established the Cheese Lane Foundry in 1704.   Initially he cast brass pots, but by 1705, he moved on to using iron.<ref name=\"Cox, 128-9\">Cox, 128-9.</ref><ref>Hereford Record Office, E12/VI/DFf/1-3.</ref>  A young [[Welsh people|Welsh]] [[apprentice]], John Thomas,<ref>[[Arthur Raistrick]], ''Dynasty of Ironfounders: The Darbys of Coalbrookdale'' (Bannisdale Press, London 1953: 2 edn, Sessions Book Trust, York 1989), 20.</ref> solved the problem by using sand for the mould, with a special casting box and [[core (manufacturing)|core]].<ref name=rolt>Rolt, L.T.C., \"Great Engineers\", 1962, G. Bell and Sons Ltd, ISBN</ref> Using this casting method Darby could cast pots of sufficient thinness and lightness. Darby took out a patent on the new casting method in 1707,<ref>English patent, 380, dated 18 April 1707.</ref>  Darby's successors sold pots over wide areas of England and Wales, and had a virtual monopoly in the trade.<ref>B. Trinder, ''The Darbys of Coalbrookdale'' (Phillimore, Chichester 1974), 24-5.</ref>  For this he used a [[reverberatory furnace|reverberatory air furnace]] of a kind developed by [[Sir Clement Clerke, 1st Baronet|Sir Clement Clerke]], initially for smelting lead near Bristol, and applied by him or his son [[Sir Talbot Clerke, 2nd Baronet|Talbot]] to iron founding at [[Vauxhall]].<ref name=\"Clerke\">{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W.  | title = Sir Clement Clerke and the adoption of coal in metallurgy  | journal = Transactions of the Newcomen Society  | volume = 73  | issue = 1  | pages = 39\u201340  | date = 2001  | url =   | doi =   10.1179/tns.2001.002| id =   }}</ref>\n\n==Copper at Coalbrookdale==\nIn 1700, another group of Bristol Quakers (including Edward Lloyd and Charles Harford) had agreed to set up a brass works 'somewhere in England'.  It is not clear where, but by 1712, Caleb Lloyd, Jeffrey Pinnell, Abraham Darby and his brother-in-law Thomas Harvey had brass works at [[Coalbrookdale]].  This is likely to be linked to an increase in shipment of 'Callumy'  ([[Calamine (mineral)|Calamine]]) up the [[river Severn]] from 1704 and Darby's agreement in 1710 to open a copper mine at [[Harmer Hill]] in [[Myddle]], on behalf of a 'Company of the City of Bristol'.  However, Darby was not a partner in establishing Tern Mill, near Tern Hall (now [[Attingham Park]]) in 1709, though his partners Thomas Harvey, Lloyd and Pinnell were.<ref name=\"Cox, 128-9\"/>  At this point Darby decided to leave the brass company and concentrate on his iron founding pursuits.\n\n==Coalbrookdale furnace==\n[[File:Darby furnace UK.jpg|thumb|Darby's blast furnace, now part of the [[Coalbrookdale Museum of Iron]]]]\nDarby leased the furnace in September 1708, and set to work preparing to get it into blast.  His first account book, running from 20 October 1708 to 4 January 1710 survives.<ref>Shropshire Archives, 6001/328.</ref>  This shows the production of 'charked' coal in January 1709 and the furnace was brought into blast on 10 January.  Darby sold 81 tons of iron goods that year.<ref name= \"earliest\">{{Cite journal  \n  | last = Mott  | first = R. A.  | title = The earliest use of coke for ironmaking  \n  | journal = The Gas World, Coking Section Supplement  \n  | volume = 145   | pages =  7\u201318  | date = 5 Jan 1957  \n}}</ref><ref>Raistrick, 34.</ref>\n\nThe furnace was used for the first time on 10 January 1709 and the blast appears to have been successful. Darby was probably helped by the fact that the Shropshire 'clod coal' that he was using was fairly [[sulphur]]-free.  However, experimentation with different fuels continued for some time; for example cargoes of coal were brought up the [[River Severn|Severn]] from [[Bristol]] and [[Neath]].<ref>Cox, 131-132</ref>  Some of the molten iron from the blast was run into [[Pig iron|pigs]] and sent down the Severn for use in Bristol foundries, but much of it was used to cast pots and other cast iron goods.<ref name= \"earliest\"/><ref>Cox, 136-137</ref>\n\nThe reasons why the iron produced by Darby was not used in forges to make wrought iron have been much debated.  The reason may be partly that his pig iron was better for castings than charcoal pig iron, but the presence of silicon as an impurity made it an unattractive feedstock for [[finery forge]]s.<ref>{{Cite book  \n  | last = Hyde  | first = Charles K.  \n  | title = Technological change and the British iron industry 1700-1870  \n  | year = 1977  | location = Princeton NJ  \n  | pages = 37\u201341  \n}}</ref>   However recent work has thrown doubt on this explanation, which is based on data from the 1720s when the [[Coalbrookdale Company]] operated a forge: the forge could hardly even make a profit with charcoal pit iron.<ref>{{Cite journal  \n  | last = King   | first = Peter   \n  | title = The choice of fuel in the eighteenth-century iron industry: the Coalbrookdale accounts reconsidered  \n  | journal = Economic History Review   | volume = (early on-line article)\n  | issue =   | pages =   132\u2013156| url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/123279723/PDFSTART\n  | doi = 10.1111/j.1468-0289.2009.00517.x   \n| year = 2011 \n }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe business was partly financed by a loan from [[Thomas Goldney II]] of Bristol and by [[Graffin Prankard]] and James Peters becoming partners.  Later John Chamberlayne became a partner, and Darby's brother-in-law [[Thomas Baylies]] a manager.<ref>Cox, 131-133.</ref>\n\n==Expansion==\nIn 1712 Darby offered to instruct William Rawlinson, a fellow Quaker and [[ironmaster]], in the techniques of smelting with coke.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = Chaloner  | first = W. H.  | title = Further light on the invention of the process of smelting iron with coke  | journal =  Economic History Review |series=Series II   | volume = 2  | pages = 185\u20137  | year = 1950  | url = | doi=10.2307/2590107| jstor = 2590107 }}</ref>  Apparently, Rawlinson, the founder of the [[Backbarrow]] Iron Company in [[Furness]],<ref>{{Cite book  | last = Fell  | first = Alfred  | title = The early industrial history of Furness and district  | year = 1908  | location = Ulverston  | pages =  208}}</ref> did not take up the offer.\n\nIn 1714, Darby and his partners renewed their lease (effective from 1717) and then built a second blast furnace. This was slightly more productive in the 1720s than the Old Blast Furnace.<ref>Raistrick, 107.</ref> It is not clear when this furnace began production but it was certainly in use by 1718.<ref>Raistrick, 305.</ref>\n\nThe Company also secured [[Vale Royal Furnace]] in central [[Cheshire]], but this did not come into their possession before Abraham Darby's death.  Afterward, it was taken over by [[Thomas Baylies]] with other partners.<ref name=\"Vale\">{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W. | title = The Vale Royal Company and its rivals  | journal = Transactions of the Historical Society of Lancashire and Cheshire  | volume = 142  | pages = 1\u201318  | year = 1993 }}</ref><ref>Raistrick, 43-4.</ref>\n\nThe Company embarked on a similar venture at Dolg\u00fbn, near [[Dolgellau]], where John Kelsall was appointed as clerk, but it is probable that the furnace there was not finished until after Darby died, when his widow and the other partners sold off their lease.<ref name=\"Vale\"/><ref>Raistrick, 44.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAfter 18 months' illness, Abraham Darby died on 5 May 1717, at his home, [[Madeley Court]], [[Madeley, Shropshire]], aged 38.\n<ref name=\"odnb\">\nCox, Nancy. \"Darby, Abraham (1678\u20131717), iron founder, copper smelter, and brass manufacturer.\" in ''[[Dictionary_of_National_Biography##Oxford_Dictionary_of_National_Biography|Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (published online 23 Sep. 2004) Accessed 14 March 2020. https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-7137.\n</ref>\nHe had built a house for himself in Coalbrookdale but did not live to occupy it. He was buried in the Quaker burial-ground at [[Broseley]], Shropshire. His widow died only a few months later.\n\n==New company==\nDarby's death left the affairs of the business in a mess.  His own shares were mortgaged to Thomas Goldney, who then exchanged the debt for eight shares (of 16) in the business.  Richard Ford, who married Abraham's daughter Mary, had two shares and became manager, but on the widow's death Thomas Baylies took out [[letters of administration]] as a creditor and sought to sell the works.  Darby\u2019s eldest son, [[Abraham Darby II]], was only six years old and his two brothers younger still.  Accordingly, their uncle Joshua Sergeant bought back some of the shares on behalf of the Darby children.  The children were sent away to school,<ref>Raistrick, 48-51.</ref> and Abraham II began assisting in the management of the works in 1728 and he was awarded four shares in the company in 1732.<ref>Trinder, 26</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{unref|section|date=April 2020}}\nAbraham Darby made an important step towards the [[Industrial Revolution]]. His method of casting pots in sand provided his successors with a viable business that operated for over two centuries.\n\nSmelting iron with coke ultimately released the iron industry from the limitation imposed by the preliminary step of \"charcoal burning\" where trees were first cut and burned to make charcoal. It also shifted the fuel used for making steel from renewable wood, to a fossil fuel, which began the modern anthropogenic process of [[global warming]].\n\nCoke-smelted cast iron went into steam engines, bridges, and many of the inventions of the 19th century.  Coke smelting made possible the great quantities of iron produced which drove the Industrial Revolution.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abraham Darby II]]\n* [[Abraham Darby III]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB|no-icon=1|prescript=|wstitle=Darby, Abraham}}\n*[http://www.sedgleymanor.com/people/abraham_darby.html Abraham Darby and family biography]\n*[http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/blabrahamdarby.htm The Darby family of inventors]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050924062118/http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/darbyo.htm The Darby dynasty]\n*[http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/darby-houses/ The Darby House]\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.booneshares.com/SomeAbrahamDarbycompanies.htm |title=The Coalbrookdale Company, with which the family was associated |access-date=7 September 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212132814/http://www.booneshares.com/SomeAbrahamDarbycompanies.htm |archive-date=12 December 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n*[http://www.britainunlimited.com/Biogs/Darby.htm Britain Unlimited's page on the Darbys]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darby, Abraham I}}\n[[Category:English ironmasters]]\n[[Category:People of the Industrial Revolution]]\n[[Category:English inventors]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Foundrymen]]\n[[Category:1678 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:Quaker families]]\n[[Category:17th-century Quakers]]\n[[Category:18th-century Quakers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Shropshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n'''Abraham Darby''', in his later life called '''Abraham Darby the Elder''', now sometimes known for convenience as '''Abraham Darby I''' (14 April 1678 &ndash; 5 May 1717), was the first and best known of [[Abraham Darby (disambiguation)|several men of that name]]. Born into an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[Quaker]] family that played an important role in the [[Industrial Revolution]], Darby developed a method of producing [[pig iron]] in a [[blast furnace]] fuelled by [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] rather than [[charcoal]]. This was a major step forward in the production of iron as a raw material for the Industrial Revolution.\n\n==Early life==\nAbraham Darby was the son of John Darby, a yeoman farmer and locksmith by trade, and his wife Ann Baylies.\nHe was born at [[Woodsettle]], [[Woodsetton]], [[Staffordshire]], just across the county boundary from [[Dudley]], [[Worcestershire]]. He was descended from nobility; his great-grandmother Jane was an [[illegitimate]] child of [[Edward Sutton, 5th Baron Dudley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackcountrysociety.co.uk/articles/duddudley.htm |title=Dud Dudley and Abraham Darby: Forging New Links |author=Carl Higgs |publisher=Black Country Society |access-date=24 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219084159/http://www.blackcountrysociety.co.uk/articles/duddudley.htm |archive-date=19 February 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAbraham's great-grandmother was a sister of the whole blood to [[Dud Dudley]], who claimed to have [[Smelting|smelt]]ed iron using coke as a fuel. Unfortunately, the iron that Dudley produced was not acceptable to the charcoal ironmasters.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W. | title = Dud Dudley's contribution to metallurgy | journal = Historical Metallurgy  | volume = 36  | issue =   1| pages = 43\u201353  | year = 2002}}</ref>  However, this may have inspired his great-grandnephew Darby to perfect this novel method of smelting.\n\nIn [[Birmingham]] in the early 1690s Darby was apprenticed to Jonathan Freeth, a  fellow Quaker and a manufacturer of [[brass]] [[Mill (grinding)|mill]]s for grinding [[malt]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Trinder|first=Barrie Stuart|title=The Darbys of Coalbrookdale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJEaAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2011-12-05|year=1974|publisher=Phillimore|isbn=0-85033-191-9|page=13}}</ref> Here Darby would have seen the use of [[coke (fuel)|coke]] to fuel malting ovens, preventing the [[sulphur]] content of [[coal]] contaminating the resulting [[beer]], but also avoiding the use of the scarcer [[charcoal]] as a fuel.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |title=The Darbys of Coalbrookdale\n  |last=Trinder  |first=Barrie\n  |publisher=Phillimore & Co. / [[Ironbridge Gorge Museum Trust]]\n  |year=1991\n  |origyear=1974\n  |isbn=0-85033-791-7\n  |ref=harv\n  |pages=9\n}}</ref> The combination of these two insights was to lead to Darby's development of the coke-fuelled [[blast furnace]] in 1709.<ref>{{cite book|last=Weissenbacher|first=Manfred|title=Sources of Power: How Energy Forges Human History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dcYHzuFLZP0C&pg=PA194|accessdate=2011-11-27|year=2009|publisher=Praeger|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-0-313-35626-1|page=194}}</ref>\n\nFreeth encouraged Darby to become a highly active member in the Society of Friends, and he remained so all his life. In 1699, when he completed his apprenticeship, he married Mary Sergeant (1678\u20131718) and moved to [[Bristol]], where he set himself up as a malt mill maker.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = Cox  | first = Nancy  | title = Imagination and innovation of an industrial pioneer: The first Abraham Darby  | journal = Industrial Archaeology Review   | volume = 12  | issue = 2  | pages = 127\u2013144 at 128  | year = 1990 | doi=10.1179/iar.1990.12.2.127}}</ref>\n\n==Bristol==\nThere was a small community of [[Quakers]] in Bristol, and Darby soon gained a reputation for skill and enterprise. In 1702 Darby joined a number of fellow Quakers to form the [[Bristol Brass Company]], with works at [[Baptist Mills, Bristol|Baptist Mills]] in Bristol.  He brought in 'Dutchmen' to operate a [[brass]] battery work, making cooking pots and other [[holloware]] under a [[trip hammer]].<ref>Cox, p. 128.</ref>\n\nHe also developed a method for casting pots in '[[green sand (casting)|greensand]]' [[mould]]s, previously only used for smaller castings.  This enabled pots to be mass-produced and to be thinner than those made by the traditional process of casting in loam moulds.  For this purpose, he established the Cheese Lane Foundry in 1704.   Initially he cast brass pots, but by 1705, he moved on to using iron.<ref name=\"Cox, 128-9\">Cox, 128-9.</ref><ref>Hereford Record Office, E12/VI/DFf/1-3.</ref>  A young [[Welsh people|Welsh]] [[apprentice]], John Thomas,<ref>[[Arthur Raistrick]], ''Dynasty of Ironfounders: The Darbys of Coalbrookdale'' (Bannisdale Press, London 1953: 2 edn, Sessions Book Trust, York 1989), 20.</ref> solved the problem by using sand for the mould, with a special casting box and [[core (manufacturing)|core]].<ref name=rolt>Rolt, L.T.C., \"Great Engineers\", 1962, G. Bell and Sons Ltd, ISBN</ref> Using this casting method Darby could cast pots of sufficient thinness and lightness. Darby took out a patent on the new casting method in 1707,<ref>English patent, 380, dated 18 April 1707.</ref>  Darby's successors sold pots over wide areas of England and Wales, and had a virtual monopoly in the trade.<ref>B. Trinder, ''The Darbys of Coalbrookdale'' (Phillimore, Chichester 1974), 24-5.</ref>  For this he used a [[reverberatory furnace|reverberatory air furnace]] of a kind developed by [[Sir Clement Clerke, 1st Baronet|Sir Clement Clerke]], initially for smelting lead near Bristol, and applied by him or his son [[Sir Talbot Clerke, 2nd Baronet|Talbot]] to iron founding at [[Vauxhall]].<ref name=\"Clerke\">{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W.  | title = Sir Clement Clerke and the adoption of coal in metallurgy  | journal = Transactions of the Newcomen Society  | volume = 73  | issue = 1  | pages = 39\u201340  | date = 2001  | url =   | doi =   10.1179/tns.2001.002| id =   }}</ref>\n\n==Copper at Coalbrookdale==\nIn 1700, another group of Bristol Quakers (including Edward Lloyd and Charles Harford) had agreed to set up a brass works 'somewhere in England'.  It is not clear where, but by 1712, Caleb Lloyd, Jeffrey Pinnell, Abraham Darby and his brother-in-law Thomas Harvey had brass works at [[Coalbrookdale]].  This is likely to be linked to an increase in shipment of 'Callumy'  ([[Calamine (mineral)|Calamine]]) up the [[river Severn]] from 1704 and Darby's agreement in 1710 to open a copper mine at [[Harmer Hill]] in [[Myddle]], on behalf of a 'Company of the City of Bristol'.  However, Darby was not a partner in establishing Tern Mill, near Tern Hall (now [[Attingham Park]]) in 1709, though his partners Thomas Harvey, Lloyd and Pinnell were.<ref name=\"Cox, 128-9\"/>  At this point Darby decided to leave the brass company and concentrate on his iron founding pursuits.\n\n==Coalbrookdale furnace==\n[[File:Darby furnace UK.jpg|thumb|Darby's blast furnace, now part of the [[Coalbrookdale Museum of Iron]]]]\nDarby leased the furnace in September 1708, and set to work preparing to get it into blast.  His first account book, running from 20 October 1708 to 4 January 1710 survives.<ref>Shropshire Archives, 6001/328.</ref>  This shows the production of 'charked' coal in January 1709 and the furnace was brought into blast on 10 January.  Darby sold 81 tons of iron goods that year.<ref name= \"earliest\">{{Cite journal  \n  | last = Mott  | first = R. A.  | title = The earliest use of coke for ironmaking  \n  | journal = The Gas World, Coking Section Supplement  \n  | volume = 145   | pages =  7\u201318  | date = 5 Jan 1957  \n}}</ref><ref>Raistrick, 34.</ref>\n\nThe furnace was used for the first time on 10 January 1709 and the blast appears to have been successful. Darby was probably helped by the fact that the Shropshire 'clod coal' that he was using was fairly [[sulphur]]-free.  However, experimentation with different fuels continued for some time; for example cargoes of coal were brought up the [[River Severn|Severn]] from [[Bristol]] and [[Neath]].<ref>Cox, 131-132</ref>  Some of the molten iron from the blast was run into [[Pig iron|pigs]] and sent down the Severn for use in Bristol foundries, but much of it was used to cast pots and other cast iron goods.<ref name= \"earliest\"/><ref>Cox, 136-137</ref>\n\nThe reasons why the iron produced by Darby was not used in forges to make wrought iron have been much debated.  The reason may be partly that his pig iron was better for castings than charcoal pig iron, but the presence of silicon as an impurity made it an unattractive feedstock for [[finery forge]]s.<ref>{{Cite book  \n  | last = Hyde  | first = Charles K.  \n  | title = Technological change and the British iron industry 1700-1870  \n  | year = 1977  | location = Princeton NJ  \n  | pages = 37\u201341  \n}}</ref>   However recent work has thrown doubt on this explanation, which is based on data from the 1720s when the [[Coalbrookdale Company]] operated a forge: the forge could hardly even make a profit with charcoal pit iron.<ref>{{Cite journal  \n  | last = King   | first = Peter   \n  | title = The choice of fuel in the eighteenth-century iron industry: the Coalbrookdale accounts reconsidered  \n  | journal = Economic History Review   | volume = (early on-line article)\n  | issue =   | pages =   132\u2013156| url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/123279723/PDFSTART\n  | doi = 10.1111/j.1468-0289.2009.00517.x   \n| year = 2011 \n }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe business was partly financed by a loan from [[Thomas Goldney II]] of Bristol and by [[Graffin Prankard]] and James Peters becoming partners.  Later John Chamberlayne became a partner, and Darby's brother-in-law [[Thomas Baylies]] a manager.<ref>Cox, 131-133.</ref>\n\n==Expansion==\nIn 1712 Darby offered to instruct William Rawlinson, a fellow Quaker and [[ironmaster]], in the techniques of smelting with coke.<ref>{{Cite journal  | last = Chaloner  | first = W. H.  | title = Further light on the invention of the process of smelting iron with coke  | journal =  Economic History Review |series=Series II   | volume = 2  | pages = 185\u20137  | year = 1950  | url = | doi=10.2307/2590107| jstor = 2590107 }}</ref>  Apparently, Rawlinson, the founder of the [[Backbarrow]] Iron Company in [[Furness]],<ref>{{Cite book  | last = Fell  | first = Alfred  | title = The early industrial history of Furness and district  | year = 1908  | location = Ulverston  | pages =  208}}</ref> did not take up the offer.\n\nIn 1714, Darby and his partners renewed their lease (effective from 1717) and then built a second blast furnace. This was slightly more productive in the 1720s than the Old Blast Furnace.<ref>Raistrick, 107.</ref> It is not clear when this furnace began production but it was certainly in use by 1718.<ref>Raistrick, 305.</ref>\n\nThe Company also secured [[Vale Royal Furnace]] in central [[Cheshire]], but this did not come into their possession before Abraham Darby's death.  Afterward, it was taken over by [[Thomas Baylies]] with other partners.<ref name=\"Vale\">{{Cite journal  | last = King  | first = P. W. | title = The Vale Royal Company and its rivals  | journal = Transactions of the Historical Society of Lancashire and Cheshire  | volume = 142  | pages = 1\u201318  | year = 1993 }}</ref><ref>Raistrick, 43-4.</ref>\n\nThe Company embarked on a similar venture at Dolg\u00fbn, near [[Dolgellau]], where John Kelsall was appointed as clerk, but it is probable that the furnace there was not finished until after Darby died, when his widow and the other partners sold off their lease.<ref name=\"Vale\"/><ref>Raistrick, 44.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAfter 18 months' illness, Abraham Darby died on 5 May 1717, at his home, [[Madeley Court]], [[Madeley, Shropshire]], aged 38.\n<ref name=\"odnb\">\nCox, Nancy. \"Darby, Abraham (1678\u20131717), iron founder, copper smelter, and brass manufacturer.\" in ''[[Dictionary_of_National_Biography##Oxford_Dictionary_of_National_Biography|Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (published online 23 Sep. 2004) Accessed 14 March 2020. https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-7137.\n</ref>\nHe had built a house for himself in Coalbrookdale but did not live to occupy it. He was buried in the Quaker burial-ground at [[Broseley]], Shropshire. His widow died only a few months later.\n\n==New company==\nDarby's death left the affairs of the business in a mess.  His own shares were mortgaged to Thomas Goldney, who then exchanged the debt for eight shares (of 16) in the business.  Richard Ford, who married Abraham's daughter Mary, had two shares and became manager, but on the widow's death Thomas Baylies took out [[letters of administration]] as a creditor and sought to sell the works.  Darby\u2019s eldest son, [[Abraham Darby II]], was only six years old and his two brothers younger still.  Accordingly, their uncle Joshua Sergeant bought back some of the shares on behalf of the Darby children.  The children were sent away to school,<ref>Raistrick, 48-51.</ref> and Abraham II began assisting in the management of the works in 1728 and he was awarded four shares in the company in 1732.<ref>Trinder, 26</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{unref|section|date=April 2020}}\nAbraham Darby made an important step towards the [[Industrial Revolution]]. His method of casting pots in sand provided his successors with a viable business that operated for over two centuries.\n\nSmelting iron with coke ultimately released the iron industry from the limitation imposed by the preliminary step of \"charcoal burning\" where trees were first cut and burned to make charcoal. It also shifted the fuel used for making steel from renewable wood, to a fossil fuel, which began the modern anthropogenic process of [[global warming]].\n\nCoke-smelted cast iron went into steam engines, bridges, and many of the inventions of the 19th century.  Coke smelting made possible the great quantities of iron produced which drove the Industrial Revolution.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abraham Darby II]]\n* [[Abraham Darby III]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB|no-icon=1|prescript=|wstitle=Darby, Abraham}}\n*[http://www.sedgleymanor.com/people/abraham_darby.html Abraham Darby and family biography]\n*[http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/blabrahamdarby.htm The Darby family of inventors]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050924062118/http://www.cottontimes.co.uk/darbyo.htm The Darby dynasty]\n*[http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/our-attractions/darby-houses/ The Darby House]\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.booneshares.com/SomeAbrahamDarbycompanies.htm |title=The Coalbrookdale Company, with which the family was associated |access-date=7 September 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212132814/http://www.booneshares.com/SomeAbrahamDarbycompanies.htm |archive-date=12 December 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n*[http://www.britainunlimited.com/Biogs/Darby.htm Britain Unlimited's page on the Darbys]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darby, Abraham I}}\n[[Category:English ironmasters]]\n[[Category:People of the Industrial Revolution]]\n[[Category:English inventors]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Foundrymen]]\n[[Category:1678 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:Quaker families]]\n[[Category:17th-century Quakers]]\n[[Category:18th-century Quakers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Shropshire]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMolding (process)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Darby_I"}
